{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c3080ec2-7608-4c83-b369-fc814b93e97f","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_dHqAoW0isCIqeruKL1ykU9","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null || echo \"dotnet not installed\"","description":"Check .NET SDK version","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check .NET SDK version"}],"interactionId":"41f96138-975a-4fa5-b071-ed9300758898","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer reports that `dotnet build` CLI builds are slow for incremental builds even when nothing has changed. The overhead comes from MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every CLI invocation. Visual Studio doesn't have this issue because it keeps MSBuild loaded in-process.\n\nThe key solution here is to use the **MSBuild Build Server** (available in .NET 8+), which keeps MSBuild processes alive between builds, eliminating the startup/evaluation overhead. This is done by passing `--tl` (terminal logger) and using the build server.\n\nActually, the main recommendations are:\n\n1. **Use `dotnet build-server`** - .NET 8 introduced the MSBuild build server which keeps MSBuild processes warm between invocations. Enabled with the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` environment variable.\n\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch`** for development workflows since it maintains the build server between file changes, avoiding repeated startup costs.\n3. **Configure Directory.Build.props** to optimize incremental build behavior with appropriate properties.\n\nThe real bottleneck is that each `dotnet build` invocation spawns a fresh MSBuild process, loads the SDK, evaluates the project graph, and checks targets—adding 2-4 seconds of overhead even for no-op builds. The MSBuild server solves this by keeping processes alive across invocations.\n\nMy main recommendations are enabling the MSBuild server in .NET 8+, using `dotnet watch build` for iterative development, and trying the newer terminal logger for efficiency gains. I should verify the .NET version available to confirm these options are viable.","outputTokens":669,"requestId":"5C05:147F4E:1C9E717:2012E0E:6A07BF69"},"id":"4aba83ae-33c0-4ac4-895b-ee2d91f0c507","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:05.090Z","parentId":"fd4a5910-d04f-4121-b733-8ab5dbe2bf1b"}
