{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c61f0538-345f-4aba-afc6-c802a89bf2d0","content":"Here's my analysis:\n\n## Root Cause\n\nThe project and code are fine — the overhead is **MSBuild process startup and SDK evaluation**, not compilation. Every `dotnet build` invocation cold-starts a new MSBuild process, loads the SDK, and re-evaluates the project graph. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping MSBuild resident in-process.\n\n## Recommendations (highest impact first)\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Build Server ⭐\nThe single biggest win. Keeps an MSBuild server process warm between invocations, eliminating cold-start overhead:\n\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\ndotnet build              # 1st build: normal speed\ndotnet build              # 2nd build: much faster (server reused)\n```\n\nAdd to your shell profile (`.bashrc`/`.zshrc`) to make it permanent.\n\n### 2. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nFor rapid edit→build→test cycles, `dotnet watch` keeps the host process alive and rebuilds incrementally on file changes:\n\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\n\n### 3. Skip restore on subsequent builds\nRestore runs by default every invocation. If packages haven't changed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet build --no-restore\n```\n\n### 4. Add graph-based static restore to the project\nAvoids redundant restore evaluation overhead:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation>true</RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n---\n\n**Summary**: The MSBuild Build Server (`DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`) is the closest equivalent to what Visual Studio does and should cut no-op CLI build times from ~2-4s down to under 1s. Combine with `--no-restore` or `dotnet watch` for the best inner-loop experience.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"41f96138-975a-4fa5-b071-ed9300758898","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Great, .NET SDK 11.0 is available. The MSBuild server is available in .NET 8+.\n\nLet me provide the analysis and concrete recommendations.\n\nThe root cause: Each `dotnet build` invocation spawns a new MSBuild process → loads the SDK → evaluates the project graph → checks all targets. This startup + evaluation overhead is the 2-4 second cost even when nothing changed. Visual Studio avoids this because it keeps MSBuild loaded in-process.\n\nKey recommendations:\n\n1. **Enable the MSBuild Build Server** - Set `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1`. This keeps an MSBuild server process alive between builds, eliminating cold-start overhead. Subsequent builds reuse the warm server.\n\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch build`** - For iterative development, `dotnet watch` maintains the build host between file changes rather than restarting it each time.\n3. **Use graph-based restore** - Setting `RestoreUseStaticGraphEvaluation` prevents redundant restore evaluations during the build process.","outputTokens":719,"requestId":"5C07:1B3F6B:1C43135:1FB9BD9:6A07BF79"},"id":"cb2a3c25-7d70-4e9d-bfea-851b7ba90d91","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:51:21.532Z","parentId":"d146b964-63d4-491b-a971-4a4d4c55a1fb"}
